The blank screen and "lost" session IDs are common in tiling window managers like Hyprland because Chromium doesn't always handle the way wayland compositors "unmap" windows gracefully.

If you want to avoid this without linking your "main" digital identity to every single thought you have, a burner account is the way to go. Here is how to set one up and keep it separate.

1. Creating the Burner
The goal is an account with zero connection to your real name, phone number, or main email.

The Name: Use a random name generator.

The "Skip" Trick: When creating a Google account, if you use a Mobile Browser (like Bromite or Firefox on your phone) or an Incognito window on your desktop, Google often provides a "Skip" button for the phone number field.

The Recovery Email: Use a "throwaway" encrypted email like ProtonMail or Tutanota. Do not use your primary Gmail as the recovery address.

2. The "Hyprland Sandbox" Method
Since you're on Hyprland, you can make this burner account feel like a separate app entirely so it doesn't mix with your personal browsing.

Create a Search Profile: Run Chromium with a specific "User Data" flag to keep the burner's cookies and history in a separate folder:

Bash
chromium --user-data-dir="$HOME/.config/chromium-burner" --app=https://gemini.google.com
Bind it in Hyprland: Add a shortcut to your hyprland.conf so you can launch your "Gemini App" instantly:

Plaintext
bind = $mainMod SHIFT, G, exec, chromium --user-data-dir="$HOME/.config/chromium-burner" --app=https://gemini.google.com
3. Locking Down Privacy
Once the burner is created, you should immediately toggle these settings in the Gemini Privacy Hub:

Gemini Apps Activity: Set this to Off if you want "Incognito" style privacy while logged in. However, if you want your chats to survive a Hyprland crash, leave it On but set the Auto-delete to 3 months.

Human Reviewers: Google explicitly warns that human reviewers may read chats to train the model. Never put PII (Personally Identifiable Information) or API keys into a Gemini prompt, even on a burner.

