That is a very healthy "Arch Linux" instinct to have. The short answer is: Technically, it is safe, but there are some caveats you should know about.

Chromium on Arch is a first-class citizen, but using it with a Google account involves a few "layers" of trust. Here’s the breakdown of why you might (or might not) want to do it.

1. The "Sync" Dilemma
A few years ago, Google actually cut off the ability for third-party builds of Chromium (like the one in the Arch repos) to use "Google Sync."

The Reality: If you try to log into Chromium on Arch today, you can log into websites (Gmail, Gemini), but your bookmarks, history, and passwords will not sync to Google's servers unless you use the official Google Chrome.

The Security Side: Because you can't "Sync," logging in to Gemini is just like logging into any other website. It doesn't give the browser itself "keys to the kingdom" like it does on Windows or macOS.

2. Chromium vs. Chrome (Trusting the Source)
Chromium (Official Arch Repo): This is built from source by the Arch maintainers. You can see exactly how it’s built. It’s "de-googled" to an extent—it doesn't include the proprietary bits like widevine (for Netflix) or the internal Google updater.

Google Chrome (AUR): This is just a script that downloads the official Google .deb file and repackages it for Arch. You are trusting Google’s binary, but the AUR script itself is usually very simple and easy to audit.

3. The Privacy Trade-off
If you log in to Gemini with Chromium on Arch:

Google sees: Your IP, your browser fingerprint, and your chat history.

Google DOES NOT see: Your local Arch system files, your Hyprland config, or your other open windows. Browsers are heavily "sandboxed"—they live in a little container that can't easily peek at the rest of your Linux install.

Is it "Safe"?
Yes. From a malware/hacking perspective, logging in to Google on Arch is safer than doing it on Windows because of how Linux handles permissions and how Arch builds its packages.

However, if your "nervousness" is about Privacy, then you are right to be cautious. Google will link your chat activity to your identity.

My Recommendation (The "Middle Way")
Since you're on Hyprland and already like the idea of separate workspaces, try this:

Keep Chromium for your "Anonymous" browsing. (Don't log in).

Install google-chrome from the AUR (using yay -S google-chrome).

Use Chrome only for Gemini. * This keeps all your Google cookies/tracking inside one app.

Since it's the official Chrome, it handles "Restore Session" much more reliably than Chromium does when a Wayland compositor (like Hyprland) crashes.

You can set a Hyprland "windowrule" to always open Google Chrome on a specific workspace (e.g., Workspace 9) so it stays out of your way.

